Very aesthetic and beautifully made fountain right in front of the house where Molière died!! (which you can also see at 40 rue de Richelieu!) This fountain is at the junction of rue Molière and rue de Richelieu in the 1st arrondissement! The main bronze statue, enthroned under a portico with an imposing pediment, representing Molière seated, is due to the sculptor Bernard-Gabriel Seurre (1795-1867), and was cast by Eck and Durand3. Two feminine allegories in marble, The Serious Comedy and The Light Comedy, surround the pedestal and are the work of Jean-Jacques Pradier (1792-1852): they each hold a parchment listing the works of the great playwright!!

Fountain built by national subscription funds, it is also a monumental statue of the seated writer, in bronze, by L. Visconti, overlooking two muses, the Light Comedy and the Serious Comedy, holding parchment listing his works, in marble, by Pradier. The water is delivered by three lions' heads; formerly brought from the Notre-Dame pump on the Seine. She now suffers from an obstruction of her pool by floral arrangements preventing the functioning of the fountain. Three space invaders have been affixed.
2 invaders reactivated on both sides. I didn't know this place. The statuary is generous and successful for our great genius.
